# DEFINES
PROVIDER Openrouter
API_KEY sk-hypercanvas-ea5ae94a72a89e837e07a226742cfb68cc67d2c327570c24
API_URL https://claude-oauth-api-production.up.railway.app/api/v1
PROMPT_ENGINEER_MODEL anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5
RUN_BIN claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --effort max --model claude-sonnet-4-6
EVAL_BIN claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --effort max --model claude-sonnet-4-6
DIR ~/circuitinference
CHECKPOINT on
TIMEOUT 900

# Download a tiny model and double its inference speed
CIRCUIT Double inference TPS of a small language model:
  RUN Download SmolLM-135M GGUF (Q4_K_M, ~100MB) from HuggingFace using curl/wget. \
    Install llama-cpp-python via pip. \
    Write a baseline benchmark script (benchmark.py) that: \
    1. Loads the model with default/naive settings (1 thread, no mmap, large context) \
    2. Generates 200 tokens from the prompt "The history of computing began" \
    3. Measures tokens per second (TPS) precisely using time.perf_counter \
    4. Runs 3 warmup iterations then 5 measured iterations \
    5. Saves results to baseline_results.json with mean TPS and individual runs \
    Print the baseline TPS clearly as: BASELINE_TPS=<number>

  RUN Now optimize inference to achieve at least 2x the baseline TPS. Read baseline_results.json for the target. \
    Strategies to try (combine as many as needed): \
    - Tune n_threads to match CPU core count \
    - Enable mmap and mlock for faster model loading \
    - Reduce n_ctx to minimum needed (256 is enough for 200 token generation) \
    - Optimize n_batch (try 512, 256, 128 — find the sweet spot) \
    - Try different quantization if available (Q8_0 vs Q4_K_M tradeoffs) \
    - Use flash attention if supported \
    - Tune n_gpu_layers to 0 explicitly for CPU-only \
    - Pre-allocate KV cache \
    Write an optimized benchmark (benchmark_optimized.py) that uses the best settings found. \
    Run the same benchmark: 200 tokens, same prompt, 3 warmup + 5 measured iterations. \
    Save results to optimized_results.json. \
    Print: OPTIMIZED_TPS=<number> and SPEEDUP=<ratio>x
  EVAL Compare baseline_results.json and optimized_results.json: \
    1. Both files must exist and contain valid JSON with a "mean_tps" field \
    2. The optimized TPS must be at least 2x the baseline TPS \
    3. Both benchmarks must have generated coherent output (not garbage/empty) \
    4. The optimized benchmark must still produce valid text (optimization didn't break generation) \
    5. Print the comparison: baseline TPS, optimized TPS, speedup ratio
    RETRY 5
